summary:
Secretory IgA is the main immunoglobulin present in saliva and provides critical protection by neutralizing bacterial pathogens involved in dental caries. It functions primarily at mucosal surfaces—where caries initiate—and thus forms the basis for effective preventive vaccination strategies.  

\boxed{B}

The correct immunoglobulin targeted in vaccines aimed at preventing dental caries is secretory IgA due to its central role in protecting the oral mucosa from pathogenic microbes. As this antibody dominates salivary defenses and blocks initial bacterial adhesion, it represents the most clinically relevant candidate for such interventions.\boxed{B} 

